## §2 — Common distributions: uniform, binomial, and geometric

**A gentle opening:** Certain patterns of randomness appear again and again. A *uniform* distribution assigns equal probability to each outcome. A *binomial* distribution counts successes in a fixed number of independent trials (like flipping a coin 10 times and counting heads). A *geometric* distribution counts how many trials until the first success (like rolling until you get a 6). Each has a formula for its probabilities and its expectation.

### §2.1 — Uniform distribution: all outcomes equally likely

**Example 2.1a:** Rolling a fair die is uniform over {1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6}.

```scheme
(define (uniform-die n)
  (let ((prob (exact/rat 1 n)))
    (map (lambda (i) (list i prob))
         (seq/arithmetic 1 1 n))))

(uniform-die 6)
```

[VISUAL: Text output of the distribution list printed to the console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 2.1b:** Picking a random integer from 1 to 100 (uniform).

```scheme
(define (uniform-1-to-100)
  (let ((prob (exact/rat 1 100)))
    (list 'each-outcome-has-probability prob)))

(uniform-1-to-100)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `(each-outcome-has-probability 1/100)` printed to the console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

### §2.2 — Binomial distribution: counting successes in n trials

Flip a coin n times with success probability p. The probability of exactly k successes is:

```
P(X = k) = C(n, k) × p^k × (1−p)^(n−k)
```

where C(n, k) is the binomial coefficient \"n choose k.\"

**Example 2.2a:** Probability of exactly 3 heads in 5 coin flips (fair coin, p = 0.5).

```scheme
(define (binomial-prob n k p)
  (let ((c (comb/choose n k))
        (pk (math/pow p k))
        (qnk (math/pow (- 1 p) (- n k))))
    (* c pk qnk)))

(binomial-prob 5 3 0.5)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `0.3125` (probability 10/32) printed to the console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 2.2b:** Full binomial distribution for n=5, p=0.5.

```scheme
(define (binomial-dist n p)
  (map (lambda (k)
         (list k (binomial-prob n k p)))
       (seq/arithmetic 0 1 (+ n 1))))

(binomial-dist 5 0.5)
```

[VISUAL: Text output listing k from 0 to 5 with probabilities, printed to console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 2.2c:** Expected number of heads in 5 flips.

For a binomial distribution, E[X] = n × p.

```scheme
(define (binomial-expected n p)
  (* n p))

(binomial-expected 5 0.5)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `2.5` printed to the console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 2.2d:** Probability of at least 4 heads in 10 flips.

\"At least 4\" means k ≥ 4, so sum P(k=4) + P(k=5) + ... + P(k=10).

```scheme
(define (prob-at-least n k-min p)
  (fold + 0
        (map (lambda (k) (binomial-prob n k p))
             (seq/arithmetic k-min 1 (+ n 1)))))

(prob-at-least 10 4 0.5)
```

[VISUAL: Text output approximately `0.828` printed to the console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

### §2.3 — Geometric distribution: trials until first success

Roll a die until you get a 6. How many rolls does it take? The probability of the first success on roll k is:

```
P(X = k) = (1−p)^(k−1) × p
```

The expected number of trials is E[X] = 1/p.

**Example 2.3a:** Probability the first 6 occurs on the third roll (p = 1/6).

```scheme
(define (geometric-prob k p)
  (* (math/pow (- 1 p) (- k 1)) p))

(geometric-prob 3 (/ 1 6))
```

[VISUAL: Text output approximately `0.116` printed to the console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 2.3b:** Expected number of rolls until the first 6.

```scheme
(define (geometric-expected p)
  (/ 1 p))

(geometric-expected (/ 1 6))
```

[VISUAL: Text output `6` printed to the console (on average, it takes 6 rolls).]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 2.3c:** Geometric distribution for first 10 outcomes, p = 0.25.

```scheme
(define (geometric-dist-10 p)
  (map (lambda (k)
         (list k (geometric-prob k p)))
       (seq/arithmetic 1 1 11)))

(geometric-dist-10 0.25)
```

[VISUAL: Text output listing k from 1 to 10 with probabilities, printed to console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

