## §6 — Probability in the real world: applications and case studies

**A gentle opening:** Probability isn't just abstract theory—it models weather, insurance, genetics, queuing, finance, machine learning, and more. Here we look at a few quick applications to see the ideas in action.

### §6.1 — The birthday problem: collisions in random samples

In a room of N people, what's the probability that at least two share a birthday? (Assume 365 days, birthdays uniformly distributed, ignore leap years.)

The trick: compute the probability that *all* birthdays are different, then subtract from 1.

**Example 6.1a:** Birthday collision probability for N = 23.

```scheme
(define (birthday-collision n)
  (let loop ((k 0) (p-all-diff 1.0))
    (if (= k n)
        (- 1.0 p-all-diff)
        (loop (+ k 1) (* p-all-diff (/ (- 365 k) 365.0))))))

(birthday-collision 23)
```

[VISUAL: Text output approximately `0.507` (just over 50% chance of a collision).]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 6.1b:** Birthday collision probability for N = 50.

```scheme
(birthday-collision 50)
```

[VISUAL: Text output approximately `0.970` (97% chance).]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

### §6.2 — Coupon collector: how many trials to see all outcomes?

A cereal box contains one of N different coupons, chosen uniformly at random. How many boxes must you buy, on average, to collect all N coupons?

The expected number is N × (1 + 1/2 + 1/3 + ... + 1/N), the N-th harmonic number times N.

**Example 6.2a:** Expected boxes to collect 6 coupons.

```scheme
(define (harmonic n)
  (fold + 0 (map (lambda (k) (/ 1.0 k))
                 (seq/arithmetic 1 1 (+ n 1)))))

(define (coupon-collector n)
  (* n (harmonic n)))

(coupon-collector 6)
```

[VISUAL: Text output approximately `14.7` printed to console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 6.2b:** Expected boxes to collect 52 coupons (a full deck).

```scheme
(coupon-collector 52)
```

[VISUAL: Text output approximately `235.6` printed to console.]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

### §6.3 — Gambler's ruin: the probability of going broke

A gambler starts with $k and plays a fair game (win or lose $1 with equal probability) until reaching $0 (ruin) or $N (goal). What's the probability of ruin?

For a fair game, P(ruin | start at k) = (N − k) / N.

**Example 6.3a:** Start with $5, goal $10—probability of ruin.

```scheme
(define (gamblers-ruin k N)
  (/ (- N k) N))

(gamblers-ruin 5 10)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `0.5` (50% chance of ruin).]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

**Example 6.3b:** Start with $1, goal $100—probability of ruin.

```scheme
(gamblers-ruin 1 100)
```

[VISUAL: Text output `0.99` (99% chance of ruin).]

<!-- BUILD: run standalone, print result. -->

